    <div id="featured" class="section active">
      <div class="artwork-grid">
        <div class="artwork-card">
          <div class="artwork-image">
            <img src="images/sunset.jpg" alt="last light" style="width:100%; height:100%; object-fit:cover;" />
          </div>
          <div class="artwork-content">
            <h3 class="artwork-title">last light/ untitiled</h3>
            <p class="artwork-medium">acrylic on canvas</p>
            <p class="artwork-description">I made this when was learning to let go of old habits or outgrown friendships. Endings dont always have to be dramatic or climatic. They can be silent and sort of peaceful? This was my way of being at peace with it.</p>

          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="artwork-card" title="camera-like observation">
          <div class="artwork-image">
            <img src="images/camera.JPG" alt="the observer" style="width:100%; height:100%; object-fit:cover;" />
          </div>
          <div class="artwork-content">
            <h3 class="artwork-title">the observer</h3>
            <p class="artwork-medium">charcoal on paper</p>
            <p class="artwork-description">This piece reflects the time when I first moved to America and felt the need to blend in. I became quiet for the first few years, intentionally watching like a camera capturing moments. I studied how people spoke, moved, and interacted, then replayed those moments in my head at home, practicing how to fit in. This drawing is a tribute to that version of me, the one who observed to adapt, to belong.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="artwork-card" title="soft bloom">
          <div class="artwork-image">
            <img src="images/lily.JPG" alt="lily" style="width:100%; height:100%; object-fit:cover;" />
          </div>
          <div class="artwork-content">
            <h3 class="artwork-title">soft bloom</h3>
            <p class="artwork-medium">oil on canvas</p>
            <p class="artwork-description">This piece was done in the spring, usually my favourite season. It's when things tend to start over to me, when everything, including nature, wakes up. But that year, I didn't feel any of that. I felt stuck, even as the world around me bloomed. I was unsure if the "reset" would ever happen. This painting was done solely on that feeling.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="artwork-card" title="my stripes aren't black and white">
          <div class="artwork-image">
            <img src="images/zebra.JPG" alt="identity stripes" style="width:100%; height:100%; object-fit:cover;" />
          </div>
          <div class="artwork-content">
            <h3 class="artwork-title">identity stripes</h3>
            <p class="artwork-medium">chalk pastel on canvas</p>
            <p class="artwork-description">This piece started with a pronunciation debate: "zeh-bruh" vs "zee-bruh." It reminded me of how much I had to relearn after moving countries. Zebra stripes blur into each other, and so do the different parts of my identity.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="artwork-card" title="rendered bone and shared humanity">
          <div class="artwork-image">
            <img src="images/skull.JPG" alt="what remains" style="width:100%; height:100%; object-fit:cover;" />
          </div>
          <div class="artwork-content">
            <h3 class="artwork-title">what remains</h3>
            <p class="artwork-medium">charcoal on paper</p>
            <p class="artwork-description">Honestly, I chose the skull as a subject partly because I really wanted to push my rendering skills; getting those technical details and the way light and shadow play across bone is something I very much enjoy. but the more time I spent on it, the more I couldn't help but notice how I felt towards it. what remains is a reminder of how we all have a shared foundation no matter how different we may appear on the outside. we all return to this fundamental structure at the end.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

